WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.946 --> 00:00:03.784
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:07.095 --> 00:00:08.820
-Hello, my name's
Yukio Lippit and I'm

00:00:08.820 --> 00:00:12.170
the faculty director of the
Arts at the Radcliffe Institute.

00:00:12.170 --> 00:00:15.490
And I'd like to extend a
warm welcome to all of you

00:00:15.490 --> 00:00:18.930
to this very special event,
the opening and celebration

00:00:18.930 --> 00:00:22.050
of our exhibition of the
artist Matika Wilbur, titled

00:00:22.050 --> 00:00:25.040
Seeds of Culture:
Portraits and Stories

00:00:25.040 --> 00:00:28.500
of Native American Women at
Radcliffe's Johnson-Kulukundis

00:00:28.500 --> 00:00:29.840
Family gallery.

00:00:29.840 --> 00:00:32.630
Now we have a wonderful
program, which

00:00:32.630 --> 00:00:34.400
includes special
musical performances,

00:00:34.400 --> 00:00:37.840
and we'll be hearing from
Matika Wilbur herself.

00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:41.210
But first, we would like to
acknowledge the Massachusetts

00:00:41.210 --> 00:00:44.320
Nipmuc and Wampanoag
tribes, whose land we

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:46.560
are on this evening.

00:00:46.560 --> 00:00:49.580
And begin with the blessing
by Mary Anne Hendricks,

00:00:49.580 --> 00:00:55.830
who is Sachem or paramount
chief, of the Natick Nipmuc.

00:00:55.830 --> 00:00:58.270
-Hello.

00:00:58.270 --> 00:01:06.940
[NON-ENGLISH] Oh, my
dear creator, hear me.

00:01:06.940 --> 00:01:09.750
I want to acknowledge the
Radcliffe Institute and Harvard

00:01:09.750 --> 00:01:12.327
University Native
American Program

00:01:12.327 --> 00:01:14.160
for the interest they've
shown in attempting

00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:18.140
to end the exploitation
of indigenous persons.

00:01:18.140 --> 00:01:20.980
I also want to bless the
many tribes represented here

00:01:20.980 --> 00:01:25.470
tonight, and the first people
on whose land we stand.

00:01:25.470 --> 00:01:28.560
Too often we have been
faced with ignorance.

00:01:28.560 --> 00:01:30.335
For example, referring
to our regalia

00:01:30.335 --> 00:01:34.600
as costumes, used in culturally
inappropriate and derogatory

00:01:34.600 --> 00:01:37.980
term, team names,
and statesmanship

00:01:37.980 --> 00:01:40.310
we no longer exist.

00:01:40.310 --> 00:01:43.430
Well to quote one of our
native Nipmuc scholars,

00:01:43.430 --> 00:01:46.900
Kristen Wyman she said,
"For hundreds of years,

00:01:46.900 --> 00:01:48.625
our people have been
used and exploited

00:01:48.625 --> 00:01:52.290
in the colonizer's pursuit
of greed and power.

00:01:52.290 --> 00:01:54.740
Using our identity
for any means,

00:01:54.740 --> 00:01:58.810
without validating our existence
is contradictory in nature,

00:01:58.810 --> 00:02:01.950
and only spreads the
seeds of ignorance.

00:02:01.950 --> 00:02:08.389
If one truly supports--" I think
I'm a little stiff at this age.

00:02:16.780 --> 00:02:20.830
"If one truly supports
bringing our culture to life,

00:02:20.830 --> 00:02:24.370
one will allow that culture
to speak for itself.

00:02:24.370 --> 00:02:28.970
Matika Wilbur, Native American
photographer and documentarian,

00:02:28.970 --> 00:02:33.840
is doing just that, allowing
culture to speak for itself.

00:02:33.840 --> 00:02:37.100
She is spreading the seeds
of truth and knowledge.

00:02:37.100 --> 00:02:40.800
Please bless Matika Wilbur
on her journey, and may

00:02:40.800 --> 00:02:45.480
society learned
from her endeavors."

00:02:52.240 --> 00:02:56.170
-Thank you very much,
Mary Anne Hendricks.

00:02:56.170 --> 00:02:59.640
By way of introducing today's
featured artist, Matika

00:02:59.640 --> 00:03:02.700
and performers, I'd like to
note that this exhibition marks

00:03:02.700 --> 00:03:05.730
a culminating moment of two
aspects of the Radcliffe

00:03:05.730 --> 00:03:06.840
Institute.

00:03:06.840 --> 00:03:09.820
And the first is our
research theme for the year,

00:03:09.820 --> 00:03:12.660
in partnership with HUNAP,
Harvard University Native

00:03:12.660 --> 00:03:15.920
American Program, which is the
study of indigenous peoples

00:03:15.920 --> 00:03:17.420
and will be marked
by our conference

00:03:17.420 --> 00:03:20.960
tomorrow in this very
gym, titled Native Peoples

00:03:20.960 --> 00:03:23.680
Native Politics, which
begins at 9:00 AM.

00:03:23.680 --> 00:03:27.070
And actually,
there is a postcard

00:03:27.070 --> 00:03:30.470
of the event on
seats for all of you,

00:03:30.470 --> 00:03:33.570
which will also feature
Matika as a participant,

00:03:33.570 --> 00:03:36.920
as well as many other
distinguished speakers.

00:03:36.920 --> 00:03:39.290
The second aspect is that
this is the culmination

00:03:39.290 --> 00:03:41.040
of a heady first
year in the life

00:03:41.040 --> 00:03:43.130
of our new gallery
at Radcliffe, which

00:03:43.130 --> 00:03:45.540
opened only this past October.

00:03:45.540 --> 00:03:49.280
And because our arts program in
the academic ventures division

00:03:49.280 --> 00:03:52.780
strives to champion the
arts as really a unique way

00:03:52.780 --> 00:03:55.900
of understanding the world
in forms that are not always

00:03:55.900 --> 00:03:58.230
foregrounded in other
ways of knowing,

00:03:58.230 --> 00:04:00.440
through particular
forms of experimentation

00:04:00.440 --> 00:04:05.550
and innovation, the senses,
memory, intimate experience

00:04:05.550 --> 00:04:06.590
and empathy.

00:04:06.590 --> 00:04:08.460
We feel that we found
the ideal artist

00:04:08.460 --> 00:04:11.960
with whom to work in Matika.

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:15.640
Matika Wilbur is a critically
acclaimed photographer, writer,

00:04:15.640 --> 00:04:17.760
and social documentarian.

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:20.370
She's a member of the
Swinomish and Tulalip tribes

00:04:20.370 --> 00:04:22.010
of the state of
Washington, where

00:04:22.010 --> 00:04:25.092
she was raised in a family
of commercial fisherman.

00:04:25.092 --> 00:04:27.050
I'd like to extend a warm
welcome to her mother

00:04:27.050 --> 00:04:29.890
Nancy, and nephew Treyton who
are with us in the audience

00:04:29.890 --> 00:04:32.430
today.

00:04:32.430 --> 00:04:35.328
[APPLAUSE]

00:04:38.720 --> 00:04:40.690
Matika went on to
study photography

00:04:40.690 --> 00:04:42.730
at the Brooks
Institute in California

00:04:42.730 --> 00:04:46.300
and the Rocky Mountain School
of Photography in Montana.

00:04:46.300 --> 00:04:50.890
Over 10 years ago, she began to
develop a monumental aspiration

00:04:50.890 --> 00:04:53.200
that has led to her work today.

00:04:53.200 --> 00:04:55.230
To help develop
a body of imagery

00:04:55.230 --> 00:04:58.210
in cultural representations
of native peoples

00:04:58.210 --> 00:05:01.850
to counteract the relentlessly
insipid one dimensional

00:05:01.850 --> 00:05:06.450
stereotypes circulating
in mainstream media,

00:05:06.450 --> 00:05:10.310
historical textbooks,
and the culture industry.

00:05:10.310 --> 00:05:13.520
To create, in her own words,
positive indigenous role

00:05:13.520 --> 00:05:16.520
models, to do justice to
the richness and diversity

00:05:16.520 --> 00:05:19.860
and lived experiences
of Indian country.

00:05:19.860 --> 00:05:23.130
In 2012, she sold everything
in her Seattle apartment

00:05:23.130 --> 00:05:26.560
and created Project 562,
which reflects her commitment

00:05:26.560 --> 00:05:30.680
to visit, engage and
photograph all 562

00:05:30.680 --> 00:05:34.050
plus Native American sovereign
territories in the United

00:05:34.050 --> 00:05:35.460
States.

00:05:35.460 --> 00:05:38.840
This project has driven her to
travel hundreds of thousands

00:05:38.840 --> 00:05:42.710
of miles, many in
her RV, The Big Girl.

00:05:42.710 --> 00:05:45.920
But also by horseback
through the Grand Canyon,

00:05:45.920 --> 00:05:48.320
by train, plane, and boat.

00:05:48.320 --> 00:05:51.330
By foot across
all 50 states, she

00:05:51.330 --> 00:05:53.880
reflects a remarkable
way of being an artist

00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:55.750
in the contemporary world.

00:05:55.750 --> 00:06:00.310
Kickstarter-funded with a large
community of online supporters,

00:06:00.310 --> 00:06:02.460
sleeping on sofas,
she is welcomed

00:06:02.460 --> 00:06:05.850
and hosted by strangers who
soon become friends, and share

00:06:05.850 --> 00:06:08.960
the aspirations of the
artist in her project.

00:06:08.960 --> 00:06:11.010
The photographs that
Matika takes reflect

00:06:11.010 --> 00:06:14.550
her consummate craftsmanship,
beautiful black and white

00:06:14.550 --> 00:06:17.300
images that selectively
incorporate color,

00:06:17.300 --> 00:06:20.300
and showcase are subjects
in vital mutualism

00:06:20.300 --> 00:06:23.860
with the lands on which they
live, in which they steward.

00:06:23.860 --> 00:06:26.560
But her virtuoso technique
is only one aspect

00:06:26.560 --> 00:06:29.900
of the social and cultural
meaning of the works.

00:06:29.900 --> 00:06:32.180
They are one product of
her dynamic engagement

00:06:32.180 --> 00:06:34.790
with native communities,
in which she takes the time

00:06:34.790 --> 00:06:38.790
to understand the stories and
histories of particular tribes,

00:06:38.790 --> 00:06:42.300
each particular tribe, each
individual, and experience

00:06:42.300 --> 00:06:48.280
what shapes entirely the way
the portrait comes to be.

00:06:48.280 --> 00:06:51.900
One gets the sense that these
works reflect true partnerships

00:06:51.900 --> 00:06:54.255
between artist and sitter.

00:06:54.255 --> 00:06:55.630
The photographs
that you will see

00:06:55.630 --> 00:06:59.000
in the gallery or but a
small but truly remarkable

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:00.960
sample of her work.

00:07:00.960 --> 00:07:02.820
Because Radcliffe is
an institution that

00:07:02.820 --> 00:07:06.140
has historically been dedicated
to the education of women,

00:07:06.140 --> 00:07:08.790
we were moved and delighted
when Matika proposed

00:07:08.790 --> 00:07:11.060
to curate a show
for us, focusing

00:07:11.060 --> 00:07:16.000
on Native American women,
the women of Project 562.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:18.280
What you witness in the
gallery through the selection

00:07:18.280 --> 00:07:21.430
is wide ranging diversity and
richness of the identities

00:07:21.430 --> 00:07:25.920
and experiences, the stories
of Native American women.

00:07:25.920 --> 00:07:29.760
You will encounter teachers,
daughters, linguists,

00:07:29.760 --> 00:07:36.540
activists, artists, mothers,
PhDs, elders, professionals,

00:07:36.540 --> 00:07:38.690
grandmothers, Ivy
League students,

00:07:38.690 --> 00:07:40.750
and community organizers.

00:07:40.750 --> 00:07:42.820
They are accompanied
by a booklet that

00:07:42.820 --> 00:07:46.180
convey the words and stories
of these individuals,

00:07:46.180 --> 00:07:50.300
and also an audio track that
fills the room with songs,

00:07:50.300 --> 00:07:52.920
prayers, and the texture
and timber of the voices

00:07:52.920 --> 00:07:55.360
of these individuals.

00:07:55.360 --> 00:07:57.390
Collectively, these
representations

00:07:57.390 --> 00:08:01.640
convey intimate experience,
but also epic tradition.

00:08:01.640 --> 00:08:05.220
The entire range of human
emotions is represented.

00:08:05.220 --> 00:08:10.170
The sadness and trauma of
genocide, colonization,

00:08:10.170 --> 00:08:16.120
but also an abundance of hope,
determination, joy, and humor,

00:08:16.120 --> 00:08:17.790
and complexity.

00:08:17.790 --> 00:08:19.530
The resourcefulness
and strategies

00:08:19.530 --> 00:08:21.680
by which these women
negotiate identity

00:08:21.680 --> 00:08:23.760
and their multiple points
of cultural reference

00:08:23.760 --> 00:08:26.180
in the contemporary world.

00:08:26.180 --> 00:08:28.470
These stories are all framed
against very different

00:08:28.470 --> 00:08:33.490
landscapes, the landscapes of
the 562, desert, valley, river,

00:08:33.490 --> 00:08:37.070
ocean, mountains,
coast, snow scape.

00:08:37.070 --> 00:08:39.120
Indeed, in the
gallery, Matika's work

00:08:39.120 --> 00:08:42.100
has managed to create
its own cosmology

00:08:42.100 --> 00:08:44.620
of the many different
regions and narratives

00:08:44.620 --> 00:08:47.700
of native communities
everywhere.

00:08:47.700 --> 00:08:50.690
All of us who have worked on
the exhibition at the Radcliffe

00:08:50.690 --> 00:08:55.080
Institute, including the
members of the Academic Ventures

00:08:55.080 --> 00:08:59.230
division, our colleagues
in events, communications,

00:08:59.230 --> 00:09:02.750
facilities, the Fellows
office, the Dean's office,

00:09:02.750 --> 00:09:04.880
as well as our
friends and partners

00:09:04.880 --> 00:09:08.370
and collaborators at HUNAP,
directed by Shelly Lowe,

00:09:08.370 --> 00:09:11.260
would like to convey
heartfelt thanks to Matika,

00:09:11.260 --> 00:09:15.020
who had given as tireless
energy, will, artistry

00:09:15.020 --> 00:09:17.640
and enthusiasm to this project.

00:09:17.640 --> 00:09:20.300
We'd like to thank our
exhibition advisor, Adrienne

00:09:20.300 --> 00:09:23.970
Keene and members of team 562.

00:09:23.970 --> 00:09:26.430
And also we would like
to thank the women

00:09:26.430 --> 00:09:28.540
in the portraits in the
gallery for allowing

00:09:28.540 --> 00:09:32.580
us to play a small role in
helping to tell their stories,

00:09:32.580 --> 00:09:37.230
and to reimagine the
richness of Indian country.

00:09:37.230 --> 00:09:40.280
Let me briefly describe
how this hour will proceed.

00:09:40.280 --> 00:09:43.700
I'd like to introduce next,
our two guest performers

00:09:43.700 --> 00:09:46.560
before asking Matika herself
to come to the podium

00:09:46.560 --> 00:09:48.410
to address this audience.

00:09:48.410 --> 00:09:51.330
After this presentation,
we will invite all of you

00:09:51.330 --> 00:09:53.260
across the yard to the gallery.

00:09:53.260 --> 00:09:56.930
We look forward to welcoming
you for a reception accompanying

00:09:56.930 --> 00:09:58.570
the opening.

00:09:58.570 --> 00:10:02.630
Now, our first performer
is Leah Shenandoah,

00:10:02.630 --> 00:10:06.760
who is a Oneida Wolf clan member
of the Iroquois Confederacy.

00:10:06.760 --> 00:10:09.060
She comes from a lineage
of distinguished artists

00:10:09.060 --> 00:10:13.020
and musicians, and her work
with her mother, Grammy Award

00:10:13.020 --> 00:10:17.420
winning Joanne Shenandoah, has
gained international acclaim.

00:10:17.420 --> 00:10:19.200
She has won numerous
awards, including

00:10:19.200 --> 00:10:23.180
debut artist of the year in 2014
by the Native American Music

00:10:23.180 --> 00:10:26.110
Awards, and best
alternative recording.

00:10:26.110 --> 00:10:27.870
She's performed
all over the world,

00:10:27.870 --> 00:10:30.270
including at the
Vatican, the White House,

00:10:30.270 --> 00:10:33.000
and before His Holiness,
the Dalai Lama.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.566
We are privileged
to be next in line

00:10:35.566 --> 00:10:36.690
at the Radcliffe Institute.

00:10:36.690 --> 00:10:39.520
Please join me in
welcoming Leah Shenandoah.

00:10:43.800 --> 00:10:46.230
-So, I'm Leah Shenandoah.

00:10:46.230 --> 00:10:49.430
My native name is Kaha whi'tha,
which means she carries along.

00:10:49.430 --> 00:10:52.340
And I will sing the song
we sang at the Vatican,

00:10:52.340 --> 00:10:57.030
and in front of His
Holiness the Dalai Lama.

00:10:57.030 --> 00:10:59.160
[NON-ENGLISH SINGING]

00:12:22.600 --> 00:12:26.100
[APPLAUSE]

00:12:30.600 --> 00:12:33.620
So the next one
I'm going to sing

00:12:33.620 --> 00:12:38.040
is not an album or
anything, so bear with me.

00:12:38.040 --> 00:12:40.676
It's called Frankenhearted.

00:12:40.676 --> 00:12:52.325
[SINGING] Early morning bird
song exalting sunrise, sunrise.

00:12:55.350 --> 00:13:06.828
Heartbeat pounding, my little
breath filled with wonder,

00:13:06.828 --> 00:13:13.516
do you lie awake too?

00:13:13.516 --> 00:13:24.966
Do on your cheek, heavens and
hell, tucked beneath your feet?

00:13:24.966 --> 00:13:33.110
I loved you once,
I can't try again.

00:13:33.110 --> 00:13:41.010
But I am happy,
yeah, for resting,

00:13:41.010 --> 00:13:45.040
I am reborn every morning.

00:13:47.720 --> 00:13:57.064
Lovers embrace, a
ghostly remembrance.

00:13:57.064 --> 00:14:06.760
Not even a trace,
my fiery ache leaves

00:14:06.760 --> 00:14:15.450
me frakenhearted, but
stronger than before.

00:14:15.450 --> 00:14:23.876
So I bless your sorrows, empty
promises, and better tomorrows.

00:14:27.620 --> 00:14:35.850
I loved you once
as the raven cries

00:14:35.850 --> 00:14:47.670
and interruption
of my beauty sleep.

00:14:47.670 --> 00:14:49.170
[APPLAUSE]

00:14:49.170 --> 00:14:51.170
That one's not recorded.

00:14:57.670 --> 00:15:01.050
The third one is off
my Nammy winning album,

00:15:01.050 --> 00:15:02.790
which is called
Weight of the World.

00:15:02.790 --> 00:15:06.390
This is about my
progression, finding self

00:15:06.390 --> 00:15:10.030
love, which I think is one
of the most difficult things

00:15:10.030 --> 00:15:11.380
to do in this day and age.

00:15:14.362 --> 00:15:23.360
[SINGING] Weight of the
world, put a curve in my neck.

00:15:23.360 --> 00:15:29.105
I shuddered from
years of disrespect.

00:15:32.320 --> 00:15:42.192
Recently, I discovered
my true self,

00:15:42.192 --> 00:15:48.618
hidden behind years of neglect.

00:15:57.410 --> 00:16:06.350
I am my higher self.

00:16:06.350 --> 00:16:10.610
I am full of sunsets.

00:16:13.650 --> 00:16:16.940
I am my higher self.

00:16:16.940 --> 00:16:20.890
I am full of sunsets.

00:16:20.890 --> 00:16:27.020
Light shine bright,
beautiful, and correct.

00:16:40.390 --> 00:16:43.636
My feet, no they don't waver.

00:16:43.636 --> 00:16:47.370
My path is in step.

00:16:47.370 --> 00:16:58.936
Dancing in the moonlight,
my energy connects all.

00:17:09.006 --> 00:17:11.988
[APPLAUSE]

00:17:17.960 --> 00:17:19.069
Now I go.

00:17:19.069 --> 00:17:22.260
I have to say happy
birthday Matika.

00:17:22.260 --> 00:17:23.410
I had to do it.

00:17:23.410 --> 00:17:24.630
You're the best.

00:17:24.630 --> 00:17:26.331
Thank you so much for having me.

00:17:26.331 --> 00:17:28.977
[APPLAUSE]

00:17:28.977 --> 00:17:31.610
-Thank you very much, Leah.

00:17:31.610 --> 00:17:35.960
Our next performer, Laura
Ortman is White Mountain Apache,

00:17:35.960 --> 00:17:38.760
and is a Brooklyn based
composer, musician,

00:17:38.760 --> 00:17:40.020
and visual artist.

00:17:40.020 --> 00:17:43.410
Based on her expertise in a wide
range of musical instruments,

00:17:43.410 --> 00:17:47.260
but most notably, violin,
electric guitar, and vocals,

00:17:47.260 --> 00:17:49.130
she's formed a number
of musical groups

00:17:49.130 --> 00:17:52.020
that are performed around
the world, including

00:17:52.020 --> 00:17:56.830
Dust Dive from 2000 onward,
National Braid from 2001

00:17:56.830 --> 00:18:00.360
onward, and The Coast Orchestra,
and All Native American

00:18:00.360 --> 00:18:04.880
Orchestral ensemble in 2008.

00:18:04.880 --> 00:18:08.960
This year, she'll release
her third solo album, My Soul

00:18:08.960 --> 00:18:10.450
Remainer.

00:18:10.450 --> 00:18:13.900
She will perform
original songs that

00:18:13.900 --> 00:18:16.400
are inspired by
Matika's show, and she

00:18:16.400 --> 00:18:19.080
says, "The presence of everyone
who has come to see it,

00:18:19.080 --> 00:18:20.760
all of you, all of us."

00:18:20.760 --> 00:18:23.190
Please join me in
welcoming Laura Ortman

00:18:23.190 --> 00:18:26.634
[APPLAUSE]

