00:30:02.300 --> 00:30:05.690
I'd like to share messages
that have been entrusted

00:30:05.690 --> 00:30:08.560
to me on the road,
and some of the hard

00:30:08.560 --> 00:30:10.785
earned discoveries
from the road.

00:30:14.960 --> 00:30:17.990
So for the past
three years, I've

00:30:17.990 --> 00:30:22.160
been on this adventurous
sojourn into Indian country.

00:30:22.160 --> 00:30:26.425
I set off with the intention to
photograph every one of tribes

00:30:26.425 --> 00:30:32.520
in the United States, 562
federally recognized tribes

00:30:32.520 --> 00:30:34.280
at its inception.

00:30:34.280 --> 00:30:36.290
Why?

00:30:36.290 --> 00:30:38.390
To change the way we
see native America.

00:30:40.950 --> 00:30:48.690
In that time, I've realized
that the best way to see,

00:30:48.690 --> 00:30:51.890
is first to listen.

00:30:51.890 --> 00:30:54.620
And what have I
listened to mostly

00:30:54.620 --> 00:30:57.290
for the last several years?

00:30:57.290 --> 00:31:02.630
Indigenous stories of
every imaginable variety.

00:31:02.630 --> 00:31:06.390
The stories from Turtle Island.

00:31:06.390 --> 00:31:11.110
And I want to tell you the
story of Turtle Island,

00:31:11.110 --> 00:31:14.030
it's one of my favorites.

00:31:14.030 --> 00:31:16.710
And it goes a little
something like this.

00:31:16.710 --> 00:31:18.370
And it should be
said that this is

00:31:18.370 --> 00:31:22.280
shared by so many communities
across Turtle Island.

00:31:22.280 --> 00:31:24.600
So, you might have heard
a different version

00:31:24.600 --> 00:31:27.530
of this story, and if you want
to argue about it afterwards,

00:31:27.530 --> 00:31:30.500
I'm down with that.

00:31:30.500 --> 00:31:35.150
So long, long ago,
when the world was new

00:31:35.150 --> 00:31:37.520
and there was no
land, only water,

00:31:37.520 --> 00:31:42.390
powerful beings lived in a
place called the sky world.

00:31:42.390 --> 00:31:46.390
One day, a curious,
young, expecting woman

00:31:46.390 --> 00:31:50.270
dug a hole at the base
of the tree of life,

00:31:50.270 --> 00:31:55.460
until she could see through
to the other side below.

00:31:55.460 --> 00:31:56.910
And you know, she's curious.

00:31:56.910 --> 00:32:00.050
She can't help but
peek through the hole.

00:32:00.050 --> 00:32:04.650
And suddenly, she
starts to slip.

00:32:04.650 --> 00:32:07.040
And she starts reaching
and grabbing for everything

00:32:07.040 --> 00:32:09.260
that she can find, and she
gets herself some dirt,

00:32:09.260 --> 00:32:13.250
and she grabs a few seeds, and
she begins to fall, and fall,

00:32:13.250 --> 00:32:17.290
and tumble into the vastness.

00:32:17.290 --> 00:32:19.920
She's spinning and
turning and floating

00:32:19.920 --> 00:32:24.710
through the expanse, past the
moon, towards the blue dot.

00:32:24.710 --> 00:32:27.910
And all of the animals
below, the winged beings

00:32:27.910 --> 00:32:30.830
and sea creatures,
they see her falling.

00:32:30.830 --> 00:32:35.220
And they say the to each
other, if we don't help her,

00:32:35.220 --> 00:32:38.380
she's going to
make a huge splash,

00:32:38.380 --> 00:32:41.440
and that is going
to ruin our day.

00:32:41.440 --> 00:32:47.010
And so, they decide to save her.

00:32:47.010 --> 00:32:51.260
So the birds, they fly up
above, and they catch her,

00:32:51.260 --> 00:32:53.300
and they soften her fall.

00:32:53.300 --> 00:32:57.710
And they place her on the
back of a giant turtle.

00:32:57.710 --> 00:33:01.730
Sky Woman gives
birth to two babies,

00:33:01.730 --> 00:33:07.720
and from those seeds,
earth and babies,

00:33:07.720 --> 00:33:12.430
the world is formed
and dance into being

00:33:12.430 --> 00:33:16.592
and became the Turtle Island
that we walk upon right now.

00:33:19.896 --> 00:33:21.836
I have another story for you.

00:33:24.590 --> 00:33:28.870
A long time ago, there
was only darkness.

00:33:28.870 --> 00:33:33.060
A man, god created,
the heaven and earth.

00:33:33.060 --> 00:33:35.310
And the earth was
without form, and void,

00:33:35.310 --> 00:33:38.640
and darkness was upon
the face of deep.

00:33:38.640 --> 00:33:41.960
And the spirit of God moved
upon the face of the waters,

00:33:41.960 --> 00:33:45.820
and God said, "Let there be
light," and there was light.

00:33:45.820 --> 00:33:49.980
God created night and
day, the sun and the moon,

00:33:49.980 --> 00:33:51.730
and all the creatures
of the world.

00:33:51.730 --> 00:34:00.730
And finally, he creates human,
man first, and then a woman.

00:34:00.730 --> 00:34:02.250
Adam and Eve.

00:34:02.250 --> 00:34:05.470
And he places
everything and everyone

00:34:05.470 --> 00:34:07.970
into one garden,
a perfect world,

00:34:07.970 --> 00:34:11.409
where there's no sickness,
no death, no hate, no hunger.

00:34:11.409 --> 00:34:17.540
There's only one rule, and
you know the rest of story.

00:34:17.540 --> 00:34:20.449
One of my favorite
authors, Thomas King,

00:34:20.449 --> 00:34:22.980
he wrote a book called
The Truth about Stories:

00:34:22.980 --> 00:34:24.750
A Native Narrative.

00:34:24.750 --> 00:34:28.080
He starts with the big
picture, a comparison

00:34:28.080 --> 00:34:29.940
of this indigenous
creation story,

00:34:29.940 --> 00:34:33.280
like the one I just told
you, in the book of Genesis

00:34:33.280 --> 00:34:36.010
of Judeo Christian traditions.

00:34:36.010 --> 00:34:40.429
The story of Sky Woman
introduces the talking animals

00:34:40.429 --> 00:34:43.760
almost straight away,
which is, as King

00:34:43.760 --> 00:34:47.449
says, a bit of a problem.

00:34:47.449 --> 00:34:49.929
The chatty fish and
friendly rabbits

00:34:49.929 --> 00:34:53.710
of indigenous literature allow
people to label [? ablet ?]

00:34:53.710 --> 00:34:59.700
as simplistic, and indigenous
societies as primitive.

00:34:59.700 --> 00:35:02.360
But as King shows,
the talking animals

00:35:02.360 --> 00:35:04.520
are actually quite
sophisticated.

00:35:04.520 --> 00:35:06.380
They speak of a
world where balance

00:35:06.380 --> 00:35:11.050
is the norm, where the
world is shared, where chaos

00:35:11.050 --> 00:35:14.020
is turned into an organization.

00:35:14.020 --> 00:35:17.710
Compare that with Judeo
Christian worldviews, where

00:35:17.710 --> 00:35:22.680
in Genesis, hierarchy,
individualism, and organization

00:35:22.680 --> 00:35:27.810
degenerate into chaos,
accompanied by aggression,

00:35:27.810 --> 00:35:29.931
an enemy.

00:35:29.931 --> 00:35:36.030
The Eden story is why
Western society favors order,

00:35:36.030 --> 00:35:38.960
rationality, and
material constructs,

00:35:38.960 --> 00:35:41.910
along with systems of
judgment, superiority, and male

00:35:41.910 --> 00:35:42.780
domination.

00:35:42.780 --> 00:35:46.720
The primary role of
traditional indigenous story,

00:35:46.720 --> 00:35:50.000
on the other hand, was
creating and fostering

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:52.430
equality between
all living things.

00:35:55.240 --> 00:35:56.990
At the heart of Sky
Woman's creation

00:35:56.990 --> 00:36:00.840
story is the idea of
universal equality,

00:36:00.840 --> 00:36:05.450
and importance of the
female essence and instinct,

00:36:05.450 --> 00:36:07.940
stewardship, and knowledge.

00:36:07.940 --> 00:36:10.580
It cherishes and
cultivates equality

00:36:10.580 --> 00:36:13.800
between the males
and the females,

00:36:13.800 --> 00:36:18.640
and especially the roles,
and all of creation.

00:36:18.640 --> 00:36:24.050
As it happens, so
many of the stories

00:36:24.050 --> 00:36:26.690
I've been given
in my journey also

00:36:26.690 --> 00:36:31.330
originate from and
relate to native women.

00:36:31.330 --> 00:36:33.320
I understand that
these stories are

00:36:33.320 --> 00:36:36.810
fundamental to how we see
and understand the world

00:36:36.810 --> 00:36:38.530
and ourselves.

00:36:38.530 --> 00:36:46.520
As King says, the truth about
stories is that's all we are.

00:36:46.520 --> 00:36:51.810
I have to tell you
though, the stories

00:36:51.810 --> 00:36:54.860
that I've been hearing
from native women

00:36:54.860 --> 00:36:58.915
all over the country
have lain heavily.

00:37:03.340 --> 00:37:07.560
When I sit down to listen to our
people, especially our women,

00:37:07.560 --> 00:37:10.370
they erupt with their
innermost stories.

00:37:10.370 --> 00:37:12.940
For some reason,
they want me to know.

00:37:12.940 --> 00:37:14.810
Maybe it's because
they understood

00:37:14.810 --> 00:37:18.080
that you and I would be sitting
here together in this room

00:37:18.080 --> 00:37:20.320
and I'd be sharing
stories with you,

00:37:20.320 --> 00:37:22.440
and that maybe these
stories would someday

00:37:22.440 --> 00:37:24.040
save somebody's life.

00:37:24.040 --> 00:37:28.270
Or maybe, it is just because
desperately, somewhere,

00:37:28.270 --> 00:37:31.920
we all yearn to be justified
by the telling of our truths.

00:37:34.850 --> 00:37:37.550
And the stories that
I've heard are the kind

00:37:37.550 --> 00:37:40.570
that are hard to repeat.

00:37:40.570 --> 00:37:45.160
Grandmas tell me about what
happened to them in IHS

00:37:45.160 --> 00:37:50.120
clinics, of how they've gone
in to have their first baby,

00:37:50.120 --> 00:37:53.770
and were never able to
conceive again, only

00:37:53.770 --> 00:37:57.040
to find out years later
that they'd been sterilized

00:37:57.040 --> 00:37:58.710
without their consent.

00:37:58.710 --> 00:38:03.690
Victims of a de facto
government, one child policy.

00:38:03.690 --> 00:38:07.440
Married women tell me about
their abusive husbands,

00:38:07.440 --> 00:38:11.920
of the violence, and
loneliness, and despair,

00:38:11.920 --> 00:38:15.490
and their fear of leaving.

00:38:15.490 --> 00:38:21.060
One lady told me about how
she was raped in the army,

00:38:21.060 --> 00:38:24.800
then was demoted
when she saw justice.

00:38:24.800 --> 00:38:28.740
Upon returning home with a
mixed race child born of rape,

00:38:28.740 --> 00:38:35.190
she was made to feel like an
outcast in her own community.

00:38:35.190 --> 00:38:37.950
Women talk about there
alarm about tribal children

00:38:37.950 --> 00:38:42.650
committing suicide,
as many already have.

00:38:42.650 --> 00:38:45.620
We talk about and sheds
tears for our elders

00:38:45.620 --> 00:38:48.430
that are passing away, and
with their passing is also

00:38:48.430 --> 00:38:50.470
the death of our
indigenous languages.

00:38:50.470 --> 00:38:53.210
Aunties talk about the
plants that are dying,

00:38:53.210 --> 00:38:56.380
the water not returning, and
creatures around them at risk.

00:38:56.380 --> 00:38:59.130
Women tell me how
difficult it is

00:38:59.130 --> 00:39:03.700
to choose a mate when
racist policies determine

00:39:03.700 --> 00:39:06.090
their future
children's opportunity

00:39:06.090 --> 00:39:08.820
for tribal citizenship.

00:39:08.820 --> 00:39:12.340
And women speak with me about
the difficulty of fitting

00:39:12.340 --> 00:39:16.150
into academic environments,
when the faces, books,

00:39:16.150 --> 00:39:20.060
and spaces around them
do not include them.

00:39:20.060 --> 00:39:22.880
Teachers express the ways
that teaching to the test

00:39:22.880 --> 00:39:24.720
inhibits their ability
to teach the truths

00:39:24.720 --> 00:39:26.530
about native America.

00:39:26.530 --> 00:39:28.740
Single mothers
share their struggle

00:39:28.740 --> 00:39:32.720
to find money to make rent.

00:39:32.720 --> 00:39:35.580
It's a lot.

00:39:35.580 --> 00:39:39.090
They tell me stories
about race, and caste,

00:39:39.090 --> 00:39:43.440
and how their bodies are
used to perpetuate both.

00:39:43.440 --> 00:39:47.030
High caste women are
sexually restricted,

00:39:47.030 --> 00:39:52.740
while women at the bottom
are sexually exploited.

00:39:52.740 --> 00:39:55.830
And while I wanted
to come here tonight

00:39:55.830 --> 00:39:59.360
and share desperately with you,
stories of beauty and light

00:39:59.360 --> 00:40:02.010
and love and nothing but
chuckle and happiness and joy,

00:40:02.010 --> 00:40:03.665
because after all,
it's my birthday

00:40:03.665 --> 00:40:04.915
and we're trying to celebrate.

00:40:08.920 --> 00:40:11.218
I felt like I had to be a
little real with you tonight.

00:40:14.890 --> 00:40:17.300
I have to tell you that
these experiences articulate

00:40:17.300 --> 00:40:20.590
our current
socioeconomic situation.

00:40:20.590 --> 00:40:24.200
Native American women are the
most victimized in the country.

00:40:24.200 --> 00:40:26.880
Three out of four
have experienced

00:40:26.880 --> 00:40:31.170
sexual assault or domestic
abuse in their lifetimes.

00:40:31.170 --> 00:40:41.500
For most native women, it is not
the question of if, but when.

00:40:41.500 --> 00:40:44.840
Across the border
in Canada, there

00:40:44.840 --> 00:40:49.630
are an estimated 1,181
stolen sisters, women

00:40:49.630 --> 00:40:55.470
from age 2 to 78,
disappeared and never found.

00:40:55.470 --> 00:40:59.370
Missing, and likely murdered.

00:40:59.370 --> 00:41:03.100
There's no question that we
are in a very critical time,

00:41:03.100 --> 00:41:06.120
and a longstanding epidemic
of abuse and misuse

00:41:06.120 --> 00:41:08.500
towards our native
women and children.

00:41:08.500 --> 00:41:10.450
And these hard and
real stories are

00:41:10.450 --> 00:41:13.510
connected to the compelling
native female narrative,

00:41:13.510 --> 00:41:16.520
from Sky Woman
forward, and deserve

00:41:16.520 --> 00:41:19.070
to be told as part of
the collective voice

00:41:19.070 --> 00:41:21.730
of Indian women.

00:41:21.730 --> 00:41:24.880
But who will tell them?

00:41:24.880 --> 00:41:26.810
And how shall they be told?

00:41:29.790 --> 00:41:34.380
In our exhibition,
Seeds of Culture:

00:41:34.380 --> 00:41:37.850
The Portraits and Stories
of Native American Women,

00:41:37.850 --> 00:41:43.190
native women are here to
tell you their own stories.

00:41:43.190 --> 00:41:45.560
Native women
suffering and loss are

00:41:45.560 --> 00:41:48.370
part of the indigenous
reality that exists,

00:41:48.370 --> 00:41:50.060
that must be respected.

00:41:50.060 --> 00:41:52.780
It must be of concern to us all.

00:41:52.780 --> 00:41:57.490
I though have found, also
in our women's stories,

00:41:57.490 --> 00:42:04.100
a treasure trove of knowledge,
strength, and vision.

00:42:04.100 --> 00:42:06.230
You will meet, in
this exhibition, women

00:42:06.230 --> 00:42:10.690
that endure the crisis and
transform the narrative, women

00:42:10.690 --> 00:42:14.430
who prosper, who
become self actualized,

00:42:14.430 --> 00:42:16.460
and fight for our nationhood.

00:42:16.460 --> 00:42:21.580
Who carry our culture forward,
save our languages, seeds,

00:42:21.580 --> 00:42:25.440
histories, and lives, while
birthing our next leaders

00:42:25.440 --> 00:42:28.290
and putting to rest the
previous generation.

00:42:28.290 --> 00:42:35.210
Women fully understanding the
complexities and power of story

00:42:35.210 --> 00:42:39.920
as social shaping and crucial
to them and individual.

00:42:39.920 --> 00:42:43.530
Women like this.

00:42:43.530 --> 00:42:47.540
This is my girl [? Desi. ?]
She's great, you'd lover her.

00:42:47.540 --> 00:42:49.540
She fierce.

00:42:49.540 --> 00:42:52.270
She has that chuckle about
her that you just love.

00:42:52.270 --> 00:42:54.770
She's infectious with
light and love and energy.

00:42:54.770 --> 00:42:57.170
When you are around her, you
feel a little bit taller.

00:42:57.170 --> 00:42:58.270
It's true.

00:42:58.270 --> 00:42:59.850
And [? Desi ?] is a scholar.

00:42:59.850 --> 00:43:02.190
She's currently
enrolled in a dual PhD

00:43:02.190 --> 00:43:04.410
program with the
University of Arizona

00:43:04.410 --> 00:43:08.650
and the University of
Waikato in New Zealand.

00:43:08.650 --> 00:43:14.100
And after earning bachelor's and
master's degrees from Stanford,

00:43:14.100 --> 00:43:16.850
she grew up on the northern
Cheyenne reservation.

00:43:16.850 --> 00:43:19.070
She returned there after
her undergraduate studies,

00:43:19.070 --> 00:43:24.550
and her academic path is shaped
and formed, and for her people.

00:43:24.550 --> 00:43:29.660
She says, they call us
the fighting Cheyenne,

00:43:29.660 --> 00:43:34.030
because we fought for everything
that we have here today.

00:43:34.030 --> 00:43:36.470
I've grown up knowing
that we are here

00:43:36.470 --> 00:43:40.740
because 300 of our people
made it back from Oklahoma.

00:43:40.740 --> 00:43:43.160
They escaped in the
middle of winter

00:43:43.160 --> 00:43:48.110
after being forced into
governmental Indian territory.

00:43:48.110 --> 00:43:52.300
They were dying of
famine and disease,

00:43:52.300 --> 00:43:56.100
and so to of our chiefs,
Dull Knife and Little Wolf,

00:43:56.100 --> 00:43:59.590
decided that they were going
to make a run for freedom.

00:43:59.590 --> 00:44:03.360
And if they died along
the way, at least

00:44:03.360 --> 00:44:06.740
they died trying to get home.

00:44:06.740 --> 00:44:10.670
So this really amazing tale of
survival of what a people would

00:44:10.670 --> 00:44:13.520
do to be within their homeland.

00:44:13.520 --> 00:44:15.510
Only 300 made it.

00:44:15.510 --> 00:44:18.510
They were chased by the
cavalry the entire time,

00:44:18.510 --> 00:44:22.570
in the middle of winter
for thousands of miles.

00:44:22.570 --> 00:44:27.630
And for me, that's not
history, that's my reality.

00:44:27.630 --> 00:44:30.970
That's a reality that our
people still live with.

00:44:30.970 --> 00:44:33.320
It's not something that's
written down in history books,

00:44:33.320 --> 00:44:35.850
it shapes your entire
life knowing every day

00:44:35.850 --> 00:44:40.250
that your ancestors
died for you to be here.

00:44:40.250 --> 00:44:43.460
And to me, that really
tells the strength

00:44:43.460 --> 00:44:44.450
of the Cheyenne people.

00:44:47.880 --> 00:44:52.460
One of the greatest truths
I've been given in my travels

00:44:52.460 --> 00:44:57.640
is that Native American
lands is essential to

00:44:57.640 --> 00:45:00.330
our Native American identity.

00:45:00.330 --> 00:45:02.890
Where are the people of
the blue green water?

00:45:02.890 --> 00:45:05.010
The people of the
tall pine trees?

00:45:05.010 --> 00:45:07.910
The people that live within
the sacred mountains?

00:45:07.910 --> 00:45:10.720
The people of the flowing tide?

00:45:10.720 --> 00:45:15.200
But what happens when our
relationship with the land

00:45:15.200 --> 00:45:17.740
is dramatically changed?

00:45:17.740 --> 00:45:20.060
And although we
haven't relocated,

00:45:20.060 --> 00:45:24.830
we feel displaced, because the
face of Mother Earth around us

00:45:24.830 --> 00:45:28.760
has changed so dramatically.

00:45:28.760 --> 00:45:32.430
Take for example what's
happening in Navajo Nation.

00:45:32.430 --> 00:45:34.290
This is Dana Eldridge.

00:45:34.290 --> 00:45:39.750
She's pictured during the
[NON-ENGLISH] meaning,

00:45:39.750 --> 00:45:43.090
our journey for existence.

00:45:43.090 --> 00:45:44.590
I know there's some
Navajos in here,

00:45:44.590 --> 00:45:48.582
so I look at them like I
know I didn't say that right.

00:45:48.582 --> 00:45:49.564
I'm sorry.

00:45:53.010 --> 00:45:55.230
How many Navajos do we got here?

00:45:55.230 --> 00:45:55.980
Come on.

00:45:55.980 --> 00:45:58.080
Yeah, I knew it.

00:45:58.080 --> 00:46:00.210
I'm just saying, Everywhere
I go in Indian country,

00:46:00.210 --> 00:46:02.640
I run into lots of Navajos.

00:46:02.640 --> 00:46:03.490
That's a good thing.

00:46:03.490 --> 00:46:04.800
We like you here.

00:46:04.800 --> 00:46:06.260
We're happy to be with you.

00:46:06.260 --> 00:46:07.020
Welcome.

00:46:07.020 --> 00:46:08.426
Please bring mutton.

00:46:13.904 --> 00:46:16.370
Dana is in the
middle, in the midst.

00:46:16.370 --> 00:46:17.900
When I took this
photo, we'd already

00:46:17.900 --> 00:46:20.050
walked 40 miles that day.

00:46:20.050 --> 00:46:25.070
They were walking 1,200 miles
on a pilgrimage across Navajo

00:46:25.070 --> 00:46:27.730
Nations to all four
sacred mountains

00:46:27.730 --> 00:46:31.080
to encourage the indigenous
uprising against fracking

00:46:31.080 --> 00:46:33.480
and extraction from
the Mother Earth,

00:46:33.480 --> 00:46:37.370
while returning to the sacred.

00:46:37.370 --> 00:46:40.460
Americans recognize the
dangers and toxicity

00:46:40.460 --> 00:46:44.290
of fracking in extracting
resources from Mother Earth.

00:46:44.290 --> 00:46:47.030
Navajo people, such
as Dana, however,

00:46:47.030 --> 00:46:52.481
feel the devastating
impacts firsthand.

00:46:52.481 --> 00:46:55.910
I have to tell you, when
we were out walking,

00:46:55.910 --> 00:46:58.690
there had been an
oil spill, and there

00:46:58.690 --> 00:47:03.970
was people in full hazmat suits
cleaning up the oil spill not

00:47:03.970 --> 00:47:06.280
even 10 yards away, where
little Indian babies were

00:47:06.280 --> 00:47:08.540
playing on the playground.

00:47:08.540 --> 00:47:10.830
It was so bad that
as we were walking,

00:47:10.830 --> 00:47:15.820
we had to wear scarves
around our faces.

00:47:15.820 --> 00:47:22.530
And yet, here are these children
playing in this environment.

00:47:22.530 --> 00:47:25.320
If that was
happening right here,

00:47:25.320 --> 00:47:27.930
or in downtown
Los Angeles, there

00:47:27.930 --> 00:47:29.115
would be a major uprising.

00:47:32.320 --> 00:47:36.070
And when I talked to
Dana, she explained

00:47:36.070 --> 00:47:40.390
that 42% of Navajo
Nation is unemployed.

00:47:40.390 --> 00:47:41.960
And the extractive
oil industries

00:47:41.960 --> 00:47:44.920
promised jobs and other
financial incentives,

00:47:44.920 --> 00:47:48.590
leaving people
with little choice

00:47:48.590 --> 00:47:52.680
but to sign the
exploitative leases.

00:47:52.680 --> 00:47:54.990
So here's the ladies.

00:47:54.990 --> 00:47:58.300
They say they walk to honor the
resiliency of our ancestors,

00:47:58.300 --> 00:48:01.970
who 150 years ago, were
forced to march hundreds

00:48:01.970 --> 00:48:05.640
of miles in the dead of winter
on a genocidal death march.

00:48:05.640 --> 00:48:08.180
They sacrificed and
suffered so much,

00:48:08.180 --> 00:48:11.240
so that we could live within
these four sacred mountains.

00:48:11.240 --> 00:48:13.760
And so we walk to honor
and remember them.

00:48:16.310 --> 00:48:18.950
I think in what I've
found is that the way

00:48:18.950 --> 00:48:23.690
that our land, the way
that we treat our land,

00:48:23.690 --> 00:48:28.430
is directly related to the
way that we treat our women.

00:48:28.430 --> 00:48:31.280
If we are willing to
penetrate the Earth

00:48:31.280 --> 00:48:36.760
for her natural resources, I'm
afraid of the consequences.

00:48:36.760 --> 00:48:38.782
Our women will also
feel its effects.

00:48:42.820 --> 00:48:43.320
Oops.

00:48:46.030 --> 00:48:49.460
Here we have a photo
of Miss Jenny Parker,

00:48:49.460 --> 00:48:53.510
and her granddaughter
[? Charlease. ?]

00:48:53.510 --> 00:48:57.770
And she's also from the
northern Cheyenne tribe.

00:48:57.770 --> 00:48:59.950
And for 25 years,
she was a teacher

00:48:59.950 --> 00:49:03.610
in the private Catholic
school on their reservation.

00:49:03.610 --> 00:49:07.330
Until one day, when she
was teaching at the school,

00:49:07.330 --> 00:49:12.330
and police came in uniform
and asked her to come

00:49:12.330 --> 00:49:15.130
identify a body.

00:49:15.130 --> 00:49:17.890
It was her daughter's.

00:49:17.890 --> 00:49:20.815
She'd been assaulted,
sexually assaulted, and left.

00:49:23.420 --> 00:49:28.760
And after that, Jenny
was just-- she just

00:49:28.760 --> 00:49:30.650
said she was just kind
of a broken heart.

00:49:30.650 --> 00:49:31.680
She had a heart attack.

00:49:35.420 --> 00:49:40.400
She said, she just didn't think
she would be able to go on.

00:49:40.400 --> 00:49:45.390
And then her granddaughter came
to her, and she said grandma,

00:49:45.390 --> 00:49:46.705
I'm going to take care of you.

00:49:46.705 --> 00:49:49.430
I'm going to move in with you.

00:49:49.430 --> 00:49:54.140
And little by little,
they would walk

00:49:54.140 --> 00:49:56.440
to the end of the
living room, and then

00:49:56.440 --> 00:49:58.990
to the end of the
driveway, and then

00:49:58.990 --> 00:50:01.650
to the end of the cul de sac.

00:50:01.650 --> 00:50:06.830
And slowly, little by
little, she began healing.

00:50:06.830 --> 00:50:10.300
And she says it's the
love, it's the love

00:50:10.300 --> 00:50:15.180
between our grandchildren and
our families that heal us.

00:50:18.940 --> 00:50:26.080
This is Deborah Parker
and her daughter, Carla.

00:50:26.080 --> 00:50:28.310
Yeah.

00:50:28.310 --> 00:50:32.910
And Deborah's from my
tribe, the Tulalip tribe.

00:50:32.910 --> 00:50:35.106
She's awesome.

00:50:35.106 --> 00:50:36.230
I don't know how to say it.

00:50:36.230 --> 00:50:39.280
I mean, when i was teaching in
a tribal school for five years,

00:50:39.280 --> 00:50:42.160
every Friday Deb came
and played with the kids.

00:50:42.160 --> 00:50:44.170
And that kind of
leadership to me,

00:50:44.170 --> 00:50:45.881
just-- she didn't
even have to talk

00:50:45.881 --> 00:50:47.380
about the kind of
leadership it was,

00:50:47.380 --> 00:50:49.550
she showed up all the time.

00:50:49.550 --> 00:50:53.350
And she's a major
advocate, and has

00:50:53.350 --> 00:50:55.444
advocated on behalf
of native women

00:50:55.444 --> 00:50:57.860
during the fight to reauthorize
the Violence Against Women

00:50:57.860 --> 00:51:00.035
Act, which was
held up in Congress

00:51:00.035 --> 00:51:02.410
due to specific provisions
that would protect

00:51:02.410 --> 00:51:04.660
native women and
tribal sovereignty.

00:51:04.660 --> 00:51:09.440
She says of her work
on VOWA, "As a survivor

00:51:09.440 --> 00:51:12.240
of domestic violence, I
knew that I would someday

00:51:12.240 --> 00:51:14.370
be able to help another person.

00:51:14.370 --> 00:51:16.960
I didn't really understand
the magnitude of the work

00:51:16.960 --> 00:51:19.640
that I would be doing once
I became the vice chairwoman

00:51:19.640 --> 00:51:21.680
of the Tulalip tribes.

00:51:21.680 --> 00:51:24.070
I don't think anyone
could have seen it coming,

00:51:24.070 --> 00:51:26.310
but I think my spirit new.

00:51:26.310 --> 00:51:30.850
Because that flight to D.C. was
one of the most unique flights.

00:51:30.850 --> 00:51:36.060
I was very quiet, and I knew
something was coming forward.

00:51:36.060 --> 00:51:39.480
And when you are asked
to protect someone,

00:51:39.480 --> 00:51:43.330
when you are asked
to protect a nation,

00:51:43.330 --> 00:51:46.890
it's just what you have to do.

00:51:46.890 --> 00:51:51.260
You armor up, you warrior
up, and you protect the women

00:51:51.260 --> 00:51:53.050
in your nation.

00:51:53.050 --> 00:51:56.740
It's a great honor to
do so, and all I can do

00:51:56.740 --> 00:51:59.030
is pray that I'm
able to speak justice

00:51:59.030 --> 00:52:02.910
toward the missing in
murdered indigenous women.

00:52:02.910 --> 00:52:06.990
Every person deserves
to receive justice."

00:52:06.990 --> 00:52:09.030
And you know something
incredible has recently

00:52:09.030 --> 00:52:10.410
happened?

00:52:10.410 --> 00:52:12.970
Deborah has advocated for
our tribal court system

00:52:12.970 --> 00:52:16.480
to switch over to a
restorative justice system.

00:52:16.480 --> 00:52:19.140
We will no longer be
imprisoning our people,

00:52:19.140 --> 00:52:22.240
we will only be working
towards rehabbing our people.

00:52:22.240 --> 00:52:24.240
And it's because
of women like this

00:52:24.240 --> 00:52:27.595
that we're able to see
major change in communities.

00:52:30.780 --> 00:52:31.770
How are you guys doing?

00:52:31.770 --> 00:52:34.306
You doing all
right, you with me?

00:52:34.306 --> 00:52:37.590
Damn, I know this is heavy.

00:52:37.590 --> 00:52:38.860
It was hard for me, too.

00:52:38.860 --> 00:52:40.732
Take a deep breath.

00:52:40.732 --> 00:52:42.120
You can laugh if you want.

00:52:42.120 --> 00:52:44.036
I'm just kidding, don't
laugh, it's not funny.

00:52:45.990 --> 00:52:48.470
This is Doctor Mary
Evelyn Belgarde.

00:52:48.470 --> 00:52:51.740
She's from the Pueblo of
Isleta in Okay Owinge.

00:52:51.740 --> 00:52:53.900
She's a retired professor
of Indian education

00:52:53.900 --> 00:52:55.850
from the University
of New Mexico.

00:52:55.850 --> 00:52:57.900
She's collaborated
and establishing

00:52:57.900 --> 00:53:01.490
several charters schools
focused on indigenous education.

00:53:01.490 --> 00:53:05.340
She has raised funds to support
thousands of native students.

00:53:05.340 --> 00:53:07.730
She is very passionate
about training

00:53:07.730 --> 00:53:10.030
culturally competent
teachers to work

00:53:10.030 --> 00:53:12.310
within indigenous communities.

00:53:12.310 --> 00:53:15.000
She's well versed in the
history of boarding schools

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:18.880
and governmentally engineered
systems of education

00:53:18.880 --> 00:53:21.120
and assimilation.

00:53:21.120 --> 00:53:24.690
And during our
conversation, she asked

00:53:24.690 --> 00:53:29.810
when are we going to stop
asking our children to choose

00:53:29.810 --> 00:53:34.820
between cultural education
and Western education?

00:53:34.820 --> 00:53:39.230
I think we're ready to stop
the assimilation process.

00:53:39.230 --> 00:53:41.844
The time to change is right now.

00:53:48.670 --> 00:53:49.555
This is Miss Helen.

00:53:52.752 --> 00:53:54.210
I've never talked
about Miss Helen,

00:53:54.210 --> 00:53:57.380
I just took this
photo three days ago.

00:53:57.380 --> 00:54:01.340
And she's not in the show, but
I was so moved by my experience

00:54:01.340 --> 00:54:03.830
when I met her, I had
to share it with you.

00:54:03.830 --> 00:54:11.880
Miss Helen is 87 years old,
and miss Helen is blind

00:54:11.880 --> 00:54:15.120
and she's only able to
hear out of one ear.

00:54:15.120 --> 00:54:18.860
And I just came from
Nevada, I was visiting

00:54:18.860 --> 00:54:20.100
all of the Piaute tribes.

00:54:20.100 --> 00:54:23.946
And they all said to me, Matika,
you have to go meet Miss Helen.

00:54:23.946 --> 00:54:27.470
And it's way out in the
desert, it's like four hours,

00:54:27.470 --> 00:54:32.620
way out there, nothing but res.

00:54:32.620 --> 00:54:34.220
I'm like, all right I'll go.

00:54:34.220 --> 00:54:35.900
I didn't know why
I was going, I just

00:54:35.900 --> 00:54:37.800
knew I was going
to meet Miss Helen.

00:54:37.800 --> 00:54:39.920
And I show up there,
and I'm greeted

00:54:39.920 --> 00:54:47.099
by Bird Man-- that's his name,
Bird Man-- and Miss Patty.

00:54:47.099 --> 00:54:49.640
And they're the kind of folks
that greet you in the driveway.

00:54:49.640 --> 00:54:52.140
They come out and they wave and
they show you where to park,

00:54:52.140 --> 00:54:53.990
and they immediately
feed you, and then

00:54:53.990 --> 00:54:56.240
they start telling
me their story.

00:54:56.240 --> 00:54:59.940
Bird and Patty met
on this spirit walk,

00:54:59.940 --> 00:55:05.836
and they fell in love, and then
Miss Patty contracted cancer,

00:55:05.836 --> 00:55:07.210
and decided that
she wasn't going

00:55:07.210 --> 00:55:10.810
to pursue Western
methodology of treatment,

00:55:10.810 --> 00:55:14.750
and decided that she
needed to move home.

00:55:14.750 --> 00:55:17.640
And when they got
home, there's only

00:55:17.640 --> 00:55:20.220
in Lovelock Paiute there's
only 300 tribal members.

00:55:20.220 --> 00:55:23.980
There's about 30 homes
there, and miss Helen

00:55:23.980 --> 00:55:28.740
is the last Piaute language
speaker of their community.

00:55:28.740 --> 00:55:30.320
And they brought me
over to meet her,

00:55:30.320 --> 00:55:35.819
and they said-- so I sat
down with her and I said,

00:55:35.819 --> 00:55:37.485
Miss Helen, I want
to take your picture.

00:55:37.485 --> 00:55:39.318
She goes, ah, what do
you want to take-- you

00:55:39.318 --> 00:55:40.570
don't want to take my picture.

00:55:40.570 --> 00:55:42.286
I don't even look good.

00:55:42.286 --> 00:55:46.180
Find some young, cute girl.

00:55:46.180 --> 00:55:48.920
And I said, well,
Miss Helen, I've

00:55:48.920 --> 00:55:52.100
been sent by all the
Piatues to meet you,

00:55:52.100 --> 00:55:56.320
because I understand that you're
the last language speaker.

00:55:56.320 --> 00:56:00.550
And miss Helen started crying.

00:56:00.550 --> 00:56:08.050
And she's like, it's true,
I am the last person here

00:56:08.050 --> 00:56:09.310
I have left to talk to.

00:56:12.130 --> 00:56:15.350
And then, Bird and Patty
brought over these little kids,

00:56:15.350 --> 00:56:16.850
like these seven
and eight-year-olds

00:56:16.850 --> 00:56:19.930
who they had been teaching
songs to sing to Miss Helen.

00:56:19.930 --> 00:56:23.240
And man, I gotta tell you--
I was driving away from them

00:56:23.240 --> 00:56:25.220
my way to come here.

00:56:25.220 --> 00:56:26.689
And I just had to
pull over and cry

00:56:26.689 --> 00:56:27.980
for a little bit in the desert.

00:56:32.770 --> 00:56:35.130
Imagine losing an
entire language.

00:56:37.730 --> 00:56:39.220
That's where we're at right now.

00:56:42.070 --> 00:56:45.299
That's happening all
over Indian country.

00:56:45.299 --> 00:56:46.840
And that's why it's
a great privilege

00:56:46.840 --> 00:56:51.200
to be here with you smart kids
and you smart folks tonight,

00:56:51.200 --> 00:56:52.970
because we're the
type of folks that

00:56:52.970 --> 00:56:55.330
can do something about that.

00:56:55.330 --> 00:56:58.970
And that's powerful and
profound, and moving.

00:56:58.970 --> 00:57:01.759
And that's why I
feel honored to get

00:57:01.759 --> 00:57:03.550
to take pictures of
people like Miss Helen,

00:57:03.550 --> 00:57:05.180
and share their story with you.

00:57:08.120 --> 00:57:12.010
This is Miss Jo Re
[? Lefrends, ?] and

00:57:12.010 --> 00:57:14.780
she's a student at Dartmouth.

00:57:14.780 --> 00:57:17.255
And I took this
photo at Crow Fair.

