00:57:18.820 --> 00:57:21.880
I know you've been
to Crow Fair, Frank.

00:57:21.880 --> 00:57:25.740
You know, Crow Fair is like
this rodeo and this pow-wow,

00:57:25.740 --> 00:57:28.220
and there's like a
thousand teepees set up,

00:57:28.220 --> 00:57:30.970
and I'd never stayed
in a teepee before.

00:57:30.970 --> 00:57:34.820
Like I'm from Longhouse people,
we don't stay in teepees.

00:57:34.820 --> 00:57:38.630
And I went out to Crow
Fair, and I'd never even

00:57:38.630 --> 00:57:40.609
like-- I hadn't ever
rode a horse like this

00:57:40.609 --> 00:57:41.900
and been in this kind of place.

00:57:41.900 --> 00:57:44.960
Anyway, the point
is, when I met Jo Re,

00:57:44.960 --> 00:57:48.750
I was amazed by her
strong commitment

00:57:48.750 --> 00:57:52.560
to her culture to going home
every year to be a part of Crow

00:57:52.560 --> 00:57:55.680
Fair, and to also
at the same time,

00:57:55.680 --> 00:57:59.830
be this powerhouse student,
wavering through the experience

00:57:59.830 --> 00:58:05.190
of being a young indigenous
person in a place that

00:58:05.190 --> 00:58:08.900
doesn't mirror herself.

00:58:08.900 --> 00:58:13.660
And I think it's worth
seeing in a place like this.

00:58:13.660 --> 00:58:17.730
It might be time for us to
create fostering and nurturing

00:58:17.730 --> 00:58:21.090
environments for our
Indian students to succeed.

00:58:21.090 --> 00:58:24.080
This is what we know
50% of native students

00:58:24.080 --> 00:58:27.070
drop out of high school.

00:58:27.070 --> 00:58:28.930
10%, 5%?

00:58:28.930 --> 00:58:31.380
5% go on to college.

00:58:31.380 --> 00:58:35.220
10% of those students
graduate from college.

00:58:35.220 --> 00:58:37.940
That's a major achievement gap.

00:58:37.940 --> 00:58:41.642
So when we meet young
ladies like Miss Jo Re,

00:58:41.642 --> 00:58:45.460
we have to acknowledge
how profound it

00:58:45.460 --> 00:58:50.150
is that she is there, and thank
her for her incredible courage.

