She taught me one
of the greatest

00:59:14.450 --> 00:59:17.350
lessons I've learned to date.

00:59:17.350 --> 00:59:19.970
Honestly, I didn't
even take this picture.

00:59:19.970 --> 00:59:23.490
This is another photographer
that took this picture.

00:59:23.490 --> 00:59:24.490
Mr. Kristine.

00:59:24.490 --> 00:59:28.480
And I met Rowan at
the Seed Conference,

00:59:28.480 --> 00:59:32.220
and she was handing out all of
these indigenous seeds that she

00:59:32.220 --> 00:59:35.000
had gathered and collected
from all over the country,

00:59:35.000 --> 00:59:40.750
encouraging our native sisters
to return to the ancestral

00:59:40.750 --> 00:59:42.710
position of holding seeds.

00:59:45.350 --> 00:59:49.280
She tole me something
that totally blew my mind.

00:59:49.280 --> 00:59:54.900
She said, you know what happens
Matika, when we grow food?

00:59:54.900 --> 00:59:56.560
I really, like, I fish.

01:00:00.950 --> 01:00:06.800
She says, when you plant
corn, and you go out

01:00:06.800 --> 01:00:09.780
and you talk to that corn
every day, and you sing to it,

01:00:09.780 --> 01:00:13.020
and you pollinate
it, and you water it,

01:00:13.020 --> 01:00:16.650
you develop this
incredible relationship.

01:00:16.650 --> 01:00:19.510
And then you're able to
feed it to your babies.

01:00:19.510 --> 01:00:21.310
And what happens
when you harvest

01:00:21.310 --> 01:00:25.650
it is you realize that
from that one seed

01:00:25.650 --> 01:00:31.250
you planted, what you get
is 1,000 seeds in return.

01:00:31.250 --> 01:00:34.100
We realize that the
earth is plentiful,

01:00:34.100 --> 01:00:37.720
and there is always
enough to share.

01:00:37.720 --> 01:00:41.410
There is always
enough to give away.

01:00:41.410 --> 01:00:46.600
And when we participate in
the Western capitalist system,

01:00:46.600 --> 01:00:51.350
we learn that
scarcity is the truth.

01:00:51.350 --> 01:00:54.060
We learn that we
all need our own.

01:00:54.060 --> 01:00:56.110
We need own house,
we need your own car,

01:00:56.110 --> 01:00:57.430
we need our own families.

01:01:03.346 --> 01:01:04.940
The earth is abundant.

01:01:07.730 --> 01:01:13.040
And she told me, she said--
I'm going to read to you some

01:01:13.040 --> 01:01:14.180
of her words.

01:01:14.180 --> 01:01:17.380
She said, "I've been asked to
be a vessel for their stories.

01:01:17.380 --> 01:01:20.920
I'm a Mohawk woman, who comes
from a long line of people

01:01:20.920 --> 01:01:22.720
who have tended
to soil and seeds

01:01:22.720 --> 01:01:24.300
with reverence and devotion.

01:01:24.300 --> 01:01:25.900
And it is through
these relationships

01:01:25.900 --> 01:01:28.690
with plants and seeds
that I'm finding my way

01:01:28.690 --> 01:01:34.480
home to a deeper understanding
of the magic of being human.

01:01:34.480 --> 01:01:37.260
It is my hope that through
our educational offerings

01:01:37.260 --> 01:01:42.460
that the seeds of hope can come
alive in the hearts and minds

01:01:42.460 --> 01:01:45.890
of people all over this earth.

01:01:45.890 --> 01:01:51.180
The message of the seeds is the
embodiment of hope and healing.

01:01:51.180 --> 01:01:57.120
They are saying, we are still
here, we are still vibrant,

01:01:57.120 --> 01:02:15.350
we are interconnected, we
helped nourish each other."

01:02:15.350 --> 01:02:17.220
I just think that's profound.

01:02:17.220 --> 01:02:19.470
I don't mean to awkwardly
pause for you, and for you

01:02:19.470 --> 01:02:21.880
all not to know what to do.

01:02:21.880 --> 01:02:24.230
But to me, that's
incredibly powerful,

01:02:24.230 --> 01:02:27.060
and it moves me every
time I think about it.

01:02:27.060 --> 01:02:31.410
In pre-European matrilineal
land based native America,

01:02:31.410 --> 01:02:33.370
this was self evident.

01:02:33.370 --> 01:02:36.940
Women then were responsible
for managing food preparation

01:02:36.940 --> 01:02:39.195
and distribution, along with
developing all children.

01:02:39.195 --> 01:02:41.740
And with such,
critical roles were

01:02:41.740 --> 01:02:43.370
naturally prized and respected.

01:02:43.370 --> 01:02:45.640
And in their remarkable
knowledge and cultivation

01:02:45.640 --> 01:02:48.240
of the earth, native
women realized

01:02:48.240 --> 01:02:52.890
a compelling interior truth,
that the created world was

01:02:52.890 --> 01:02:56.150
abundant, based on their
experience of the land's

01:02:56.150 --> 01:02:58.990
plentiful potential
generosity and altruism

01:02:58.990 --> 01:03:01.620
should be core human values.

01:03:01.620 --> 01:03:04.870
Women advocated this truth
in their prominent standing

01:03:04.870 --> 01:03:10.750
in the order of tribes, and set
an overwhelmingly humane tone,

01:03:10.750 --> 01:03:13.220
and so much else.

01:03:13.220 --> 01:03:15.670
In our tribes,
there was no thought

01:03:15.670 --> 01:03:18.910
of women being less or
subject to mistreatment

01:03:18.910 --> 01:03:21.500
because they were female.

01:03:21.500 --> 01:03:23.040
It was with the
arrival of whites,

01:03:23.040 --> 01:03:26.260
an alien model of resource
taking and control

01:03:26.260 --> 01:03:30.360
of intentional profit
oriented scarcity took hold.

01:03:30.360 --> 01:03:33.180
And along with other
unfathomable cultural

01:03:33.180 --> 01:03:37.740
destruction, women's land based
practices, values, and status

01:03:37.740 --> 01:03:39.150
were lost.

01:03:39.150 --> 01:03:42.310
Native Americans entered
a horrifying systemic

01:03:42.310 --> 01:03:47.000
displacement of estrangement
from the natural giving world.

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:51.870
King explains that stories
are wondrous things,

01:03:51.870 --> 01:03:53.860
and they are dangerous.

01:03:53.860 --> 01:03:58.220
It leaves us with the hope that
if we create better stories

01:03:58.220 --> 01:04:01.540
and stopped believing
in dangerous stories,

01:04:01.540 --> 01:04:05.170
we can create a better world.

01:04:05.170 --> 01:04:09.290
Because the truth about stories
is that we get the world

01:04:09.290 --> 01:04:11.030
we imagine.

01:04:11.030 --> 01:04:15.910
And in that sense, we
get the world we deserve.

01:04:15.910 --> 01:04:19.390
So thank you so much, my
friends and relatives,

01:04:19.390 --> 01:04:22.370
for listening, as I
share about my encounters

01:04:22.370 --> 01:04:25.340
with our mothers, our
sisters, our grandmothers,

01:04:25.340 --> 01:04:28.440
our indigenous women.

01:04:28.440 --> 01:04:31.270
Native female advocates
for tribal women

01:04:31.270 --> 01:04:34.200
well understand and
emphasize that our plight

01:04:34.200 --> 01:04:37.285
is a longstanding consequence
of the destruction

01:04:37.285 --> 01:04:42.470
and disruption of our
inherently matrilineal cultures.

01:04:42.470 --> 01:04:46.560
Our indigenous stories,
knowledge systems, and values,

01:04:46.560 --> 01:04:48.920
deserve appropriate
representation

01:04:48.920 --> 01:04:53.640
in cultivation in places such
as Radcliffe and Harvard.

01:04:53.640 --> 01:04:57.460
Our women deserve the right
to express those stories,

01:04:57.460 --> 01:05:01.340
their individualism,
and their bodies,

01:05:01.340 --> 01:05:06.990
free of social fictions and the
dysfunction long imposed on us.

01:05:06.990 --> 01:05:12.950
And for all of us in
our shared heritage,

01:05:12.950 --> 01:05:17.840
there is a rich transference
of power and possibility

01:05:17.840 --> 01:05:21.110
when we decide to
accept and learn

01:05:21.110 --> 01:05:25.560
of the indigenous narrative
and identity of this land.

01:05:25.560 --> 01:05:29.790
So [NON-ENGLISH]
thank you so much.

01:05:29.790 --> 01:05:35.700
